ocial situations and relationships. Based on ethnographic studies from around the world—varying from rituals and meetings over protests and conflicts to natural disasters and management—this volume analyzes generative moments through events that hold the key to understanding larger social situations. These events—including the Ashura ritual in Bahrain, social cleavages in South Africa, a Buddhist cave in Nepal, drought in Burkina Faso, an earthquake in Pakistan, the cartoon crisis in Denmark, corporate management at Bang & Olufsen, protest meetings in Europe, and flooding and urban citizenship in Mozambique—are not simply destructive disasters, crises, and conflicts, but also generative and constitutive of the social.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aEthnologyxMethodology. 0aEthnologyxPhilosophy. 0aExperience. 0aLife change events. 0aSymbolic anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aFibiger, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapferer, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapferer, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKrause-Jensen, Jakob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrøijer, Stine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKublitz, Anja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeinert, Lotte, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNielsen, Jonas Østergaard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNielsen, Morten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOestergaard, Jesper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOxlund, Bjarke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.